(2, 110, 'Silicone Impression', 'tm033-silicone-impression-material', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Silicone impression material stands as a cornerstone in modern dentistry, renowned for its versatility, accuracy, and reliability in capturing detailed impressions of the oral cavity. Composed of silicone polymers, these impression materials come in various viscosities and set times to accommodate different clinical scenarios. The silicone impression material is commonly used in both fixed and removable prosthodontics, orthodontics, and implant dentistry due to its ability to accurately replicate tooth morphology and soft tissue contours. Its hydrophobic nature ensures excellent moisture control, making it ideal for capturing precise impressions even in challenging clinical conditions. It </span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">dispensed from cartridges and mixed using an automixing system to ensure uniformity and consistency of the material. Once injected into the impression tray, it flows smoothly and evenly over the teeth and soft tissues, capturing minute details with exceptional clarity. Dental professionals appreciate silicone impressions for their dimensional stability, which prevents distortion over time and ensures accurate reproduction of the oral structures. Moreover, the elasticity of silicone impression material allows for easy removal from the mouth without tearing or distortion, contributing to a comfortable experience for the patient.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Silicone impressions offer clinicians the flexibility to choose from a range of materials tailored to specific clinical needs, including light-bodied, medium-bodied, and heavy-bodied consistencies. Light-bodied silicone is typically used for syringeable precision around the margins of preparations, while heavy-bodied silicone provides adequate bulk and support for full-arch impressions. Additionally, the advent of addition-cured silicone materials has further enhanced the accuracy and reliability of impressions, ensuring optimal fit and longevity of dental restorations. With its exceptional performance and versatility, silicone impression material continues to play a pivotal role in achieving predictable and esthetic outcomes in contemporary dental practice. Silicone impression materials are favored by dental professionals for their excellent tear strength, which ensures the integrity of the impression during removal and subsequent handling. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The ability of silicone impressions to capture fine details, such as surface texture and margin delineation, facilitates precise restorative work and contributes to the longevity of dental restorations. Furthermore, silicone impression materials exhibit minimal distortion upon removal from the mouth, allowing for accurate reproduction of the patient\'s oral anatomy. This dimensional stability is particularly advantageous when fabricating indirect restorations, such as crowns and bridges, where precision is paramount for optimal fit and function. Additionally, silicone impressions can be used in conjunction with various tray types, including stock trays, custom trays, and dual-arch trays, providing flexibility in impression-taking techniques to suit individual patient needs and preferences.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-03 23:28:02', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:41:27', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-03 23:28:02', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 11, 1, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(3, 112, 'Alginate Impression', 'alginate-impression', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Alginate impression material is a staple in dentistry, known for its versatility and ease of use. It consists primarily of sodium alginate derived from seaweed, making it biocompatible and safe for intraoral use. When mixed with water, alginate powder forms a viscous paste that can accurately capture the intricate details of a patient\'s teeth and surrounding oral structures. Dental professionals rely on alginate impressions for various purposes, including fabricating custom dental appliances such as crowns, bridges, and dentures. It is a widely-used dental material employed for capturing detailed impressions of a patient\'s teeth and surrounding oral structures. Composed primarily of sodium alginate derived from seaweed, it exhibits excellent compatibility with oral tissues and offers a safe and non-toxic option for dental procedures. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Alginate powder is mixed with water to form a viscous paste that quickly sets into a rubbery consistency when placed in the mouth. Dental professionals rely on alginate impressions for various purposes, including fabricating custom dental appliances like crowns, bridges, and dentures. Its ability to accurately reproduce intricate details of the oral cavity makes it indispensable in the field of prosthodontics and orthodontics. It is</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\"> low cost compared to other impression materials, making them accessible for a wide range of patients. Despite its advantages, alginate does have limitations, such as its tendency to shrink slightly upon setting and its relatively short working time. Nonetheless, with proper technique and handling, alginate impression remains a staple in dental practices worldwide, serving as a fundamental tool in delivering quality oral healthcare.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Alginate Impressions is relatively short, typically ranging from one to four minutes, depending on the specific formulation and environmental conditions. This quick setting time allows for efficient and comfortable impression-taking procedures for patients. However, it\'s essential for dental practitioners to work swiftly and precisely to ensure optimal results and avoid distortion of the impression. Despite its advantages, alginate impressions do have limitations, such as susceptibility to dimensional changes over time and a relatively short shelf life once mixed. Nonetheless, with proper technique and handling, alginate impression material remains an invaluable tool in modern dentistry, facilitating accurate diagnoses and the creation of high-quality dental restorations to improve patients\' oral health and aesthetics. alginate impressions are often the preferred choice for preliminary impressions due to their cost-effectiveness and ability to provide adequate detail for initial treatment planning. However, it\'s essential for dental professionals to follow manufacturer recommendations and guidelines to achieve consistent and accurate results with alginate impressions, ensuring the success of subsequent dental procedures.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 02:59:36', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:40:27', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 02:59:36', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 10, 2, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(4, 113, 'Glass Ionomer Cement', 'glass-ionomer-cement', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Glass Ionomer Cement (GIC) stands as a versatile and indispensable material in the realm of restorative dentistry, offering a plethora of benefits and applications. Composed of a unique blend of powdered glass and a liquid containing an acidic solution, GIC undergoes a chemical reaction upon mixing, resulting in the formation of a hardened material known as the glass ionomer. This innovative bonding mechanism ensures robust adhesion to tooth structure, providing exceptional retention and sealing properties crucial for the success and longevity of dental restorations.</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">One of the most remarkable qualities of GIC is its ability to release fluoride ions over time. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">This gradual release not only aids in the prevention of secondary caries but also contributes to the strengthening of adjacent tooth structure, making it particularly advantageous in pediatric dentistry and for patients prone to dental decay. GIC exhibits a coefficient of thermal expansion akin to that of natural tooth structure, mitigating the risk of marginal leakage and secondary decay, thereby bolstering the durability and stability of restorations.</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Despite its numerous merits, it\'s essential to acknowledge the limitations of GIC, particularly in terms of mechanical properties compared to composite resins. As a result, its usage may be restricted in high-load-bearing areas where greater strength and durability are required. Nevertheless, its ease of application, natural appearance, and fluoride-releasing capabilities render it a preferred choice for a wide array of restorative procedures. From filling cavities to cementing crowns and bridges, Glass Ionomer Cement continues to be a trusted ally for dental professionals worldwide, delivering reliable and aesthetically pleasing results while contributing to enhanced oral health outcomes for patients.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">It also serves as a valuable tool in preventive dentistry. Its ability to release fluoride ions plays a crucial role in remineralizing and strengthening tooth structure, aiding in the prevention of caries recurrence and progression. This makes GIC an excellent choice for applications such as pit and fissure sealants, where its fluoride-releasing properties can provide long-term protection against decay in susceptible areas. Furthermore, its biocompatibility and minimal technique sensitivity make it well-suited for use in pediatric dentistry, where patient cooperation and comfort are paramount. GIC\'s versatility extends beyond its traditional restorative and preventive applications. It can also be utilized as a luting agent for cementing indirect restorations such as crowns, bridges, and orthodontic appliances. Its ability to chemically bond to both tooth structure and various dental materials ensures a strong and durable bond, facilitating long-term success and stability of the restoration. This makes GIC a valuable asset in the armamentarium of dental professionals, offering a reliable and effective solution for a wide range of clinical scenarios. Whether addressing caries, enhancing preventive care, or securing prosthetic restorations, Glass Ionomer Cement continues to prove its value as a versatile and indispensable material in modern dentistry.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 03:57:12', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:33:58', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 03:57:12', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 11, 3, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(5, 114, 'Dental Amalgam', 'dental-amalgam', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental amalgam is a commonly used dental filling material composed of a mixture of metals, including silver, tin, copper, and mercury. It has been utilized in dentistry for over a century due to its durability, strength, and affordability. Dental amalgam is known for its silver-gray appearance and ability to withstand the forces of chewing, making it suitable for restoring posterior teeth subjected to high occlusal forces. Despite concerns about mercury content, dental amalgam is considered safe for use in dental restorations when properly handled and placed according to established protocols. However, due to aesthetic considerations and the availability of alternative materials, such as composite resin, the use of dental amalgam has declined in recent years. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">It has long been a cornerstone of restorative dentistry, valued for its durability, strength, and affordability. Composed primarily of a mixture of silver, tin, copper, and mercury, dental amalgam has been used for over a century to fill cavities and restore damaged teeth. The high content of silver in dental amalgam contributes to its excellent strength and wear resistance, making it particularly suitable for restoring posterior teeth subjected to heavy chewing forces. Additionally, the inclusion of copper in the amalgam alloy enhances its corrosion resistance and durability, ensuring long-term stability of the restoration.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The process of placing dental amalgam involves mixing the powdered alloy with liquid mercury to form a plastic mass that can be packed into the prepared cavity. Once placed, the amalgam undergoes a chemical reaction known as amalgamation, in which the mercury reacts with the other metals to form a strong, solid restoration. Dental professionals appreciate the ease of handling and manipulation of dental amalgam, as it allows for efficient placement and contouring of the restoration to achieve optimal occlusion and aesthetics. Moreover, dental amalgam exhibits a relatively low coefficient of thermal expansion, minimizing the risk of marginal leakage and secondary decay over time.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Despite its longstanding history and proven clinical performance, dental amalgam has faced scrutiny in recent years due to concerns about its mercury content and environmental impact. However, numerous studies and regulatory agencies, including the American Dental Association (ADA) and the World Health Organization (WHO), have affirmed the safety and efficacy of dental amalgam when used according to established guidelines. Dental amalgam remains a valuable treatment option, particularly in situations where durability and longevity are paramount, such as in patients with high caries risk or those requiring extensive restorations. While alternative materials like composite resins continue to gain popularity, dental amalgam continues to be a trusted and reliable choice for restoring teeth and preserving oral health.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 04:09:22', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:49:24', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:09:22', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 6, 4, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(6, 115, 'Dental Etching Agent', 'tm062-dental-etching-agent', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">A dental etching agent, also known as an etchant, is a chemical solution used in dentistry to prepare the tooth surface for bonding restorative materials such as composite resin. It typically contains phosphoric acid, which selectively removes the smear layer and creates a microporous surface on the enamel or dentin. This roughened surface enhances the mechanical retention of the adhesive, promoting strong and durable bonding between the tooth and the restorative material. Dental etching agents come in different concentrations and application forms, including liquid or gel, to suit various clinical needs and preferences. Proper application of the etchant is crucial for achieving successful adhesion and long-term clinical outcomes in dental restorations. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">Dental etching is a fundamental procedure in restorative dentistry, essential for achieving reliable adhesion between tooth structure and composite resin materials. The etching process involves the application of a mildly acidic solution, commonly phosphoric acid, to the enamel and dentin surfaces of the tooth. This acid creates microscopic pores and irregularities on the tooth surface, which enhance the mechanical interlocking of the adhesive with the tooth structure. As a result, dental etching significantly improves the bond strength and longevity of composite restorations.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">The etching solution is typically applied for a specific duration, usually around 15 to 30 seconds, depending on the manufacturer\'s instructions and the condition of the tooth. It is crucial for dental professionals to ensure complete coverage of the etchant on the tooth surface during application to achieve uniform and effective etching. After the desired etching time, the acid is thoroughly rinsed away with water to halt the etching process and remove any residual acid from the tooth surface. This step is crucial to prevent over-etching, which can weaken the tooth structure and compromise the integrity of the restoration.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">Following dental etching, a bonding agent is applied to the etched tooth surface to facilitate adhesion between the tooth and the composite resin material. The bonding agent infiltrates the micropores created by the etching process, forming a strong and durable bond with the tooth structure. Dental professionals must carefully follow the manufacturer\'s instructions for the application and curing of the bonding agent to ensure optimal bonding strength and longevity of the restoration. Once the bonding agent is applied, the composite resin material can be placed and sculpted to restore the natural form and function of the tooth.</span></p>\r\n<p> </p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 04:17:15', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:47:50', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:17:15', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 8, 5, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(7, 116, 'Dental Flowable', 'tm065-light-curable-dental-flowable-resin', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental flowable, also known as flowable composite, is a versatile dental material used for various restorative and cosmetic procedures. It is characterized by its low viscosity and fluid consistency, allowing it to flow easily into small cavities, gaps, or irregularities in the tooth structure. Dental flowable is commonly utilized for pit and fissure sealants, small cavity fillings, and as a liner under larger composite restorations. Its excellent adaptability and handling properties make it ideal for achieving seamless and esthetic results. With its ability to bond securely to tooth structure and other composite materials, dental flowable provides durable and long-lasting restorations that blend seamlessly with natural teeth. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental flowable composite resin is a versatile and indispensable material in modern dentistry, offering a wide range of applications and benefits. This low-viscosity composite resin flows easily into intricate dental cavities, narrow spaces, and areas requiring precise adaptation, making it ideal for a variety of restorative and cosmetic procedures. Dental professionals appreciate the excellent flow characteristics of these materials, which allow for effortless placement and contouring, ensuring optimal adaptation to tooth structure and margins. Flowable composites are commonly used as cavity liners, pit and fissure sealants, and as an intermediate layer in composite restorations to enhance adaptation and minimize voids.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Moreover, dental flowable composites exhibit properties that promote long-term restoration success, such as excellent wear resistance, polishability, and color stability. These materials offer reliable mechanical properties and durability, ensuring the longevity of dental restorations in the challenging oral environment. Additionally, flowable composites often contain radiopaque fillers, enabling clinicians to detect and monitor the integrity of restorations on dental radiographs. This feature enhances diagnostic capabilities and aids in the early detection of potential complications, such as secondary caries or restoration fractures.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Furthermore, the aesthetic versatility of dental flowable composites makes them an attractive choice for cosmetic dental procedures, such as direct veneers, minor reshaping, and dental bonding. Their ability to mimic the natural translucency and shade variations of tooth enamel allows for seamless integration with surrounding dentition, achieving lifelike and esthetically pleasing results. Patients appreciate the minimally invasive nature of treatments involving flowable composites, as they often require less tooth preparation and conserve healthy tooth structure. Overall, dental flowable composites represent a valuable addition to the armamentarium of dental practitioners, offering superior handling characteristics, durability, and esthetics to meet the diverse needs of patients and ensure optimal outcomes in restorative and cosmetic dentistry.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 04:21:03', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:45:25', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:21:03', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 8, 6, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(8, 117, 'Self-Curing Tooth Acrylic', 'self-curing-tooth-acrylic', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Self-curing tooth acrylic is a dental material commonly used for fabricating temporary crowns, bridges, and other dental prostheses. It consists of a powder and liquid component that are mixed together to form a malleable paste. Once applied to the prepared tooth or mold, the acrylic undergoes a chemical reaction that causes it to harden and set without the need for external curing sources. This material is valued for its strength, durability, and esthetic properties, making it suitable for temporary restorations that can withstand the forces of chewing and speaking. Self-curing tooth acrylic is an essential tool in restorative dentistry, providing patients with functional and aesthetically pleasing temporary solutions while permanent restorations are being fabricated. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Self-curing dental materials play a crucial role in modern dentistry, offering convenience and efficiency in various clinical applications. These materials, such as self-curing resin-based composites and acrylics, undergo polymerization and hardening without the need for external heat or light activation. This inherent ability to self-cure makes them particularly useful in situations where access to light or heat sources may be limited or impractical, such as in deep cavities or areas with restricted visibility.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In restorative dentistry, self-curing materials are commonly used for direct composite fillings, dental bonding procedures, and fabrication of temporary crowns and bridges. Dental professionals appreciate the predictable setting time of self-curing materials, which allows for precise manipulation and placement before the material hardens. Additionally, self-curing materials offer excellent adaptation to cavity walls and margins, ensuring a reliable seal and long-term restoration integrity. Patients benefit from the reduced chairside time associated with self-curing materials, resulting in shorter treatment durations and improved comfort during dental procedures.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Furthermore, self-curing materials find extensive use in prosthetic dentistry for the fabrication of dentures, temporary restorations, and orthodontic appliances. The ability of these materials to polymerize at room temperature eliminates the need for specialized equipment or additional processing steps, streamlining the fabrication process and reducing laboratory turnaround time. Dental laboratories rely on self-curing materials for their versatility and ease of use in creating precise and durable prosthetic devices. Whether in the dental clinic or laboratory, self-curing materials continue to be valued for their reliability, versatility, and efficiency in meeting the diverse needs of dental practitioners and their patients.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 04:25:56', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:44:20', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:25:56', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 5, 7, '', '', 1, 3, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(9, 118, 'Wax Sheet', 'wax-sheet', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Wax sheets are thin, pliable sheets typically made from a blend of natural and synthetic waxes. They are widely used in various industries, including dentistry, crafts, and food packaging. In dentistry, wax sheets are commonly employed for fabricating dental prostheses, such as crowns, bridges, and dentures, as well as for creating diagnostic wax-ups. The sheets can be easily softened and shaped using heat, allowing for precise molding and detailing. Once cooled and solidified, wax sheets provide a stable and accurate model for further dental procedures. Available in different thicknesses and colors, wax sheets offer versatility and customization options for dental professionals and artisans alike. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Wax sheets are fundamental tools in dentistry, serving a variety of purposes in both clinical and laboratory settings. Composed of pliable and moldable wax material, these sheets come in various thicknesses and formulations to meet the specific requirements of different dental procedures. One of the primary uses of wax sheets is in the fabrication of diagnostic wax-ups, where they serve as a sculpting medium for simulating the desired shape, size, and contours of dental restorations. Dental professionals utilize wax sheets to create mock-ups of crowns, bridges, veneers, and other prosthetic devices, providing patients with a visual representation of their proposed treatment outcome.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Moreover, wax sheets are indispensable in the construction of custom trays for impression-taking procedures. Dental laboratory technicians heat and adapt the wax sheets over stone models of the patient\'s dentition to fabricate trays that precisely fit the oral anatomy. These custom trays ensure accurate impression capture and enhance patient comfort during procedures. Additionally, wax sheets find utility in the creation of bite registration records, occlusal rims for denture fabrication, and wax patterns for casting metal frameworks in removable partial dentures.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The versatility of wax sheets extends beyond clinical applications, as they are also utilized in various laboratory processes. Dental technicians use wax sheets to create intricate patterns for casting metal or ceramic restorations, such as crowns, inlays, and onlays. The moldability of wax allows for precise contouring and detailing, ensuring the final restoration meets the patient\'s functional and esthetic requirements. Furthermore, wax sheets serve as a medium for dental students and professionals to practice their waxing and sculpting skills, honing their manual dexterity and proficiency in dental prosthetics. Overall, wax sheets play a vital role in dental practice, facilitating the fabrication of accurate and aesthetically pleasing dental restorations while serving as a valuable educational tool in the training of future dental professionals.</span></p>', '', 1, 9, '2024-05-04 04:31:38', 748, '', '2024-05-24 02:43:48', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:31:38', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 7, 0, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(10, 119, 'Dental Clean Scaler', 'dental-clean-scaler', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\">A dental scaler is a handheld instrument used by dental professionals to remove plaque, tartar, and calculus deposits from the teeth and along the gum line. Equipped with a pointed tip or curved blade, the scaler gently but effectively scrapes away hardened deposits without damaging the tooth enamel or surrounding tissues. Dental scalers come in various designs, including manual scalers and ultrasonic scalers, each offering unique benefits and applications. With precise control and ergonomic handles, dental scalers allow for thorough cleaning and polishing, promoting oral health and preventing gum disease. Trusted by dentists worldwide, dental scalers are essential tools in routine dental cleanings and periodontal treatments. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Essential tools used by dental professionals to remove plaque, tartar, and stains from the teeth and gums during dental cleanings and periodontal procedures. These scalers are designed to safely and effectively remove deposits from the tooth surface and below the gumline, helping to prevent oral diseases such as gingivitis and periodontitis. Dental cleaning scalers come in various shapes and sizes, each with specific features and functionalities tailored to different clinical needs and treatment objectives.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">One of the most commonly used types of dental cleaning scalers is the ultrasonic scaler, which utilizes high-frequency vibrations to break up and remove plaque and calculus from the teeth. Ultrasonic scalers consist of a handpiece connected to a power unit, which generates ultrasonic vibrations through a thin metal tip or insert. The rapid vibration of the scaler tip creates cavitation bubbles in the water stream, which disrupt plaque biofilm and dislodge tartar deposits without causing damage to the tooth surface. Ultrasonic scalers offer advantages such as reduced treatment time, improved patient comfort, and enhanced access to hard-to-reach areas compared to traditional hand scalers.</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In addition to ultrasonic scalers, dental cleaning kits may include hand scalers or curettes, which are handheld instruments with sharp, curved tips used for manual removal of plaque and calculus. Hand scalers come in various designs, such as sickle scalers, universal curettes, and gracey curettes, each with specific blade shapes and angles optimized for different tooth surfaces and periodontal conditions. Dental professionals utilize hand scalers to meticulously remove calculus deposits from the tooth surface and root surfaces, particularly in areas where ultrasonic scalers may be less effective or contraindicated.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental cleaning scalers play a crucial role in maintaining oral health and preventing periodontal diseases by effectively removing plaque and calculus from the teeth and gums. Proper selection and use of dental scalers require skill, technique, and knowledge of periodontal anatomy to ensure thorough cleaning while minimizing trauma to the soft tissues. Dental professionals adhere to strict infection control protocols when handling and sterilizing scalers to prevent cross-contamination between patients and ensure patient safety. Overall, dental cleaning scalers are indispensable tools in dental practice, contributing to optimal oral hygiene and periodontal health for patients of all ages.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 04:57:13', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:12:42', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 04:57:13', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 5, 6, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', '');
