(11, 120, 'Tissue Dispessor', 'tissue-dispessor', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">A tissue dispenser is an essential accessory in dental and medical settings, designed to provide convenient access to disposable tissues for various clinical purposes. Typically constructed from durable materials such as plastic or stainless steel, tissue dispensers are sturdy and easy to clean, ensuring hygienic usage. They are often wall-mounted or placed on countertops for easy accessibility during patient care. With their practical design, tissue dispensers help maintain a clean and organized clinical environment, promoting efficiency and professionalism. Available in various sizes and styles, tissue dispensers offer flexibility to suit the specific needs and preferences of different healthcare facilities. </span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">It appears there might be a misunderstanding regarding the term \"tissue dispissor\" as it doesn\'t seem to correspond to a recognized dental instrument. However, I can provide information on tissue dispensers, which are commonly used in dental offices for various purposes.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Tissue dispensers are essential accessories in dental offices, providing patients and dental professionals with convenient access to tissues for a wide range of clinical and personal uses. These dispensers typically consist of a container or box designed to hold a stack of disposable tissues, with a mechanism for easy retrieval and dispensing. Tissue dispensers are strategically placed throughout the dental office in areas such as patient treatment rooms, waiting areas, and restroom facilities to ensure that tissues are readily available when needed.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In clinical settings, tissue dispensers serve multiple purposes, including wiping excess saliva, water, or dental materials from the face and hands during dental procedures, providing comfort to patients during treatment, and maintaining cleanliness and hygiene in the dental operatory. Dental professionals routinely use tissues to dry and isolate the treatment area, control bleeding, and remove debris from the oral cavity. Additionally, tissues are provided to patients for personal hygiene and comfort, such as wiping the mouth or hands after dental procedures.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The design of tissue dispensers varies depending on factors such as capacity, material, and functionality. Some dispensers feature wall-mounted or countertop designs, while others are portable or freestanding for easy relocation as needed. Furthermore, tissue dispensers may incorporate features such as one-handed dispensing mechanisms, transparent windows for monitoring tissue levels, and hygienic covers or lids to protect the contents from contamination. Dental practices prioritize the regular restocking and maintenance of tissue dispensers to ensure that patients and dental staff always have access to clean tissues for optimal comfort and hygiene.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 05:03:31', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:11:18', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 05:03:31', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 4, 7, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(12, 121, 'Dental Handpiece', 'dental-handpiece', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The dental handpiece is a fundamental tool in dentistry, utilized for various procedures ranging from cavity preparation to polishing. It typically consists of a motor-driven handpiece and a detachable bur or abrasive attachment. Designed for precision and comfort, modern dental handpieces are ergonomically shaped to reduce hand fatigue during prolonged use. They offer variable speed and torque settings, allowing dentists to customize the cutting parameters according to the specific treatment needs and patient comfort. With their high-speed rotation and smooth operation, dental handpieces facilitate efficient and accurate dental treatments, enhancing both practitioner performance and patient experience. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">It is a fundamental tool in dentistry, essential for performing a wide range of dental procedures with precision and efficiency. Also known as a dental drill or dental turbine, the handpiece is a handheld instrument that utilizes rotary motion to cut, shape, and polish tooth structure and dental materials. Dental handpieces typically consist of a handle, a turbine or motor, and a rotating bur or attachment. The handle houses the motor and provides a comfortable grip for the dental professional, while the turbine or motor generates the rotational power necessary for the operation of the handpiece.</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">There are several types of dental handpieces available, including high-speed and low-speed handpieces, each designed for specific clinical applications. High-speed handpieces operate at speeds ranging from 300,000 to 400,000 revolutions per minute (RPM) and are primarily used for cavity preparation, crown and bridge preparations, and other procedures requiring rapid cutting and shaping of tooth structure. Low-speed handpieces, on the other hand, operate at slower speeds, typically between 5,000 and 40,000 RPM, and are used for tasks such as polishing, finishing, and endodontic procedures.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental handpieces may be air-driven, electric, or a combination of both, depending on the type of motor used to power the instrument. Air-driven handpieces utilize compressed air to drive the turbine, while electric handpieces feature an electric motor housed within the handpiece itself. Electric handpieces offer advantages such as consistent torque and speed control, reduced noise and vibration, and compatibility with a wider range of attachments and accessories. Additionally, some advanced electric handpieces incorporate features such as LED lighting, ergonomic designs, and programmable settings for enhanced functionality and user comfort. Overall, dental handpieces are indispensable tools in modern dentistry, enabling dental professionals to deliver high-quality dental care while maximizing patient comfort and treatment efficiency.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 05:06:17', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:10:13', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 05:06:17', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 6, 3, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(13, 122, 'Dental Sander Gun', 'dental-chair', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The dental sander gun is a specialized instrument used in dental laboratories for precise shaping and contouring of dental prostheses and restorations. It employs compressed air to deliver a stream of abrasive particles, such as aluminum oxide or diamond grit, onto the surface of dental materials. With its ergonomic design and adjustable settings, the sander gun allows technicians to achieve fine detailing and smooth finishes on various dental materials, including ceramics and acrylics. Its controlled abrasion process enables technicians to refine margins, adjust occlusion, and enhance aesthetic outcomes with accuracy and efficiency. Trusted by dental professionals for its versatility and reliability, the dental sander gun is an essential tool in the fabrication of high-quality dental restorations. </span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">It appears there might be a confusion regarding the term \"dental sander gun\" as it doesn\'t seem to correspond to a recognized dental tool or device. However, I can provide information on dental sandblasting units, which are commonly used in dental laboratories for various purposes.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental sandblasting units, also known as dental sanders or sandblasters, are specialized devices used in dental laboratories for surface preparation, cleaning, and texturing of dental prostheses, restorations, and appliances. These units typically consist of a compressed air source, an abrasive material chamber, and a handpiece with a nozzle for directing the abrasive stream onto the dental workpiece. The abrasive material, often aluminum oxide or silica particles, is propelled at high velocity through the nozzle onto the surface of the dental material, effectively removing contaminants, residues, and surface irregularities.</span><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">sandblasting units are commonly used to enhance the bond strength of dental materials by creating a roughened surface texture that promotes mechanical interlocking between the restoration and adhesive agents. For example, sandblasting is often performed on metal frameworks for ceramic restorations, dental implants, and orthodontic appliances to improve the retention and durability of the final restoration. Additionally, sandblasting units are utilized for cleaning and polishing dental prostheses, removing investment materials from castings, and adjusting the fit and contour of dental appliances.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">The use of dental sandblasting units requires skill and precision to achieve optimal results without causing damage to the dental workpiece. Dental technicians must carefully control the pressure, angle, and duration of the sandblasting process to avoid over-abrasion or surface roughness that could compromise the integrity of the restoration. Proper maintenance and calibration of sandblasting equipment are also essential to ensure consistent performance and prolong the lifespan of the device. Overall, dental sandblasting units are valuable tools in dental laboratories, offering versatility, efficiency, and precision in the preparation and finishing of dental restorations and appliances.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 05:10:00', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:08:39', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 05:10:00', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 6, 4, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(14, 123, 'Portable X-ray ', 'portable-x-ray', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">A portable X-Ray machine is a compact and versatile tool used in dental settings to capture detailed images of patients\' teeth and jawbones. Designed for mobility and convenience, it allows dental professionals to perform X-Ray examinations directly in the treatment room or even in remote locations. Equipped with advanced technology, such as digital sensors and wireless connectivity, portable X-Ray machines produce high-quality images with minimal radiation exposure to patients. Their lightweight and ergonomic design enable easy maneuverability, enhancing workflow efficiency and patient comfort. Portable X-Ray machines are indispensable assets in dental practices, enabling accurate diagnosis and treatment planning with flexibility and precision </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Also known as handheld X-ray devices or portable radiography units, are compact and lightweight imaging systems used in dental practice to capture diagnostic X-ray images with flexibility and convenience. These portable units provide dental professionals with the ability to obtain intraoral and extraoral radiographs directly at the patient\'s chairside, eliminating the need for patients to visit a separate radiography room. Portable X-ray machines typically consist of a handheld X-ray generator connected to a control panel and a digital sensor or film holder. These devices are powered by rechargeable batteries or electrical outlets, allowing for easy transport and use in various clinical settings.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">One of the primary advantages of portable X-ray machines is their versatility and mobility, enabling dental practitioners to perform diagnostic imaging procedures efficiently and effectively in diverse environments, such as hospital dental clinics, nursing homes, or mobile dental facilities. These devices offer flexibility in positioning and angulation, allowing dental professionals to capture high-quality radiographic images while accommodating patients of different ages and physical conditions. Portable X-ray machines are particularly useful for capturing emergency radiographs or imaging patients with limited mobility who may have difficulty accessing traditional X-ray units.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In addition to their convenience and mobility, portable X-ray machines utilize digital imaging technology, allowing for the immediate acquisition and viewing of radiographic images on a computer screen or handheld device. This digital workflow enhances diagnostic efficiency by enabling real-time image interpretation and facilitating communication between dental professionals and patients. Furthermore, digital radiography offers advantages such as reduced radiation exposure, enhanced image quality, and improved storage and retrieval of patient records compared to traditional film-based radiography. With the increasing adoption of digital imaging technology in dentistry, portable X-ray machines continue to play a crucial role in delivering high-quality diagnostic imaging services while improving patient comfort and safety.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 05:24:22', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:06:56', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 05:24:22', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_page_title\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_article_format\":\"standard\",\"helix_ultimate_audio\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_gallery\":\"\",\"helix_ultimate_video\":\"\"}', 5, 5, '', '', 1, 0, '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\"}', 0, '*', ''),
(15, 124, 'Light Cure', 'light-cure', '<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Light cure, also known as light curing or light polymerization, is a vital step in dental procedures involving composite resin materials. Utilizing a specialized curing light, this process initiates a chemical reaction within the composite resin, transforming it from a pliable state to a hardened, durable material. The light source emits a specific wavelength of light, typically in the blue spectrum, which activates photoinitiators within the resin, initiating the polymerization process. This ensures rapid and thorough curing of the material, allowing for efficient placement and shaping of dental restorations. With its precision and reliability, light cure technology plays a pivotal role in achieving long-lasting and aesthetically pleasing dental outcomes. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Also known as light-activated or photo-polymerization, is a vital process in dentistry used for curing various dental materials such as composite resins, sealants, and bonding agents. This technique involves the use of a high-intensity light source, typically a dental curing light, to initiate the polymerization reaction of light-curable materials. The light emitted by the curing unit activates photo-initiators within the dental material, triggering a chemical reaction that transforms the liquid or semi-solid material into a hardened solid. Light-curing offers several advantages over traditional self-curing or dual-curing methods, including faster curing times, better control over the polymerization process, and reduced post-operative sensitivity.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">Dental curing lights come in different wavelengths, such as blue light, violet light, or LED (light-emitting diode) technology, each optimized for specific dental materials and applications. LED curing lights have gained popularity in recent years due to their compact size, energy efficiency, and long-lasting performance. These lights emit high-intensity light in the blue spectrum, which corresponds to the absorption spectrum of most dental photo-initiators, ensuring efficient polymerization of light-curable materials. Additionally, LED curing lights offer adjustable power settings and various curing modes to accommodate different clinical situations and material requirements.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\">In clinical practice, light-curing is routinely used in restorative dentistry for placing and curing composite resin restorations, such as fillings, veneers, and dental bonding. The ability to rapidly cure composite materials with light allows for efficient layering and contouring of restorations, reducing chairside time and improving patient comfort. Furthermore, light-curing enables dental professionals to achieve predictable and durable bond strength between the composite material and tooth structure, ensuring long-term restoration success. With advancements in light-curing technology and materials, dental practitioners can deliver high-quality, esthetic dental restorations while optimizing treatment efficiency and patient outcomes.</span></p>', '', 1, 10, '2024-05-04 05:29:20', 748, '', '2024-05-24 03:05:49', 748, NULL, NULL, '2024-05-04 05:29:20', NULL, '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":\"\",\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":\"\",\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":\"\",\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"info_block_show_title\