(10, 'index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4', 'index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4:glass-ionomer-cement&catid=9', 'Glass Ionomer Cement', ' Glass Ionomer Cement (GIC) stands as a versatile and indispensable material in the realm of restorative dentistry, offering a plethora of benefits and applications. Composed of a unique blend of powdered glass and a liquid containing an acidic solution, GIC undergoes a chemical reaction upon mixing, resulting in the formation of a hardened material known as the glass ionomer. This innovative bonding mechanism ensures robust adhesion to tooth structure, providing exceptional retention and sealing properties crucial for the success and longevity of dental restorations.One of the most remarkable qualities of GIC is its ability to release fluoride ions over time. This gradual release not only aids in the prevention of secondary caries but also contributes to the strengthening of adjacent tooth structure, making it particularly advantageous in pediatric dentistry and for patients prone to dental decay. GIC exhibits a coefficient of thermal expansion akin to that of natural tooth structure, mitigating the risk of marginal leakage and secondary decay, thereby bolstering the durability and stability of restorations.Despite its numerous merits, it\'s essential to acknowledge the limitations of GIC, particularly in terms of mechanical properties compared to composite resins. As a result, its usage may be restricted in high-load-bearing areas where greater strength and durability are required. Nevertheless, its ease of application, natural appearance, and fluoride-releasing capabilities render it a preferred choice for a wide array of restorative procedures. From filling cavities to cementing crowns and bridges, Glass Ionomer Cement continues to be a trusted ally for dental professionals worldwide, delivering reliable and aesthetically pleasing results while contributing to enhanced oral health outcomes for patients. It also serves as a valuable tool in preventive dentistry. Its ability to release fluoride ions plays a crucial role in remineralizing and strengthening tooth structure, aiding in the prevention of caries recurrence and progression. This makes GIC an excellent choice for applications such as pit and fissure sealants, where its fluoride-releasing properties can provide long-term protection against decay in susceptible areas. Furthermore, its biocompatibility and minimal technique sensitivity make it well-suited for use in pediatric dentistry, where patient cooperation and comfort are paramount. GIC\'s versatility extends beyond its traditional restorative and preventive applications. It can also be utilized as a luting agent for cementing indirect restorations such as crowns, bridges, and orthodontic appliances. Its ability to chemically bond to both tooth structure and various dental materials ensures a strong and durable bond, facilitating long-term success and stability of the restoration. This makes GIC a valuable asset in the armamentarium of dental professionals, offering a reliable and effective solution for a wide range of clinical scenarios. Whether addressing caries, enhancing preventive care, or securing prosthetic restorations, Glass Ionomer Cement continues to prove its value as a versatile and indispensable material in modern dentistry. ', '2024-05-24 02:33:58', '7f35d4aa3e5e23418eb6dd99f1a4ff78', 1, 1, 1, '*', '2024-05-04 03:57:12', NULL, '2024-05-04 03:57:12', NULL, 0, 0, 3, );
