(93, 'com_content.article.2', '', '2024-05-24 02:41:27', 748, 5290, '047f2a51853dd4262a97a215155f863e36eba3d3', '{\"id\":\"2\",\"asset_id\":110,\"title\":\"Silicone Impression\",\"alias\":\"tm033-silicone-impression-material\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Silicone impression material stands as a cornerstone in modern dentistry, renowned for its versatility, accuracy, and reliability in capturing detailed impressions of the oral cavity. Composed of silicone polymers, these impression materials come in various viscosities and set times to accommodate different clinical scenarios. The silicone impression material is commonly used in both fixed and removable prosthodontics, orthodontics, and implant dentistry due to its ability to accurately replicate tooth morphology and soft tissue contours. Its hydrophobic nature ensures excellent moisture control, making it ideal for capturing precise impressions even in challenging clinical conditions. It <\\/span><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">dispensed from cartridges and mixed using an automixing system to ensure uniformity and consistency of the material. Once injected into the impression tray, it flows smoothly and evenly over the teeth and soft tissues, capturing minute details with exceptional clarity. Dental professionals appreciate silicone impressions for their dimensional stability, which prevents distortion over time and ensures accurate reproduction of the oral structures. Moreover, the elasticity of silicone impression material allows for easy removal from the mouth without tearing or distortion, contributing to a comfortable experience for the patient.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Silicone impressions offer clinicians the flexibility to choose from a range of materials tailored to specific clinical needs, including light-bodied, medium-bodied, and heavy-bodied consistencies. Light-bodied silicone is typically used for syringeable precision around the margins of preparations, while heavy-bodied silicone provides adequate bulk and support for full-arch impressions. Additionally, the advent of addition-cured silicone materials has further enhanced the accuracy and reliability of impressions, ensuring optimal fit and longevity of dental restorations. With its exceptional performance and versatility, silicone impression material continues to play a pivotal role in achieving predictable and esthetic outcomes in contemporary dental practice. Silicone impression materials are favored by dental professionals for their excellent tear strength, which ensures the integrity of the impression during removal and subsequent handling. <\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">The ability of silicone impressions to capture fine details, such as surface texture and margin delineation, facilitates precise restorative work and contributes to the longevity of dental restorations. Furthermore, silicone impression materials exhibit minimal distortion upon removal from the mouth, allowing for accurate reproduction of the patient\'s oral anatomy. This dimensional stability is particularly advantageous when fabricating indirect restorations, such as crowns and bridges, where precision is paramount for optimal fit and function. Additionally, silicone impressions can be used in conjunction with various tray types, including stock trays, custom trays, and dual-arch trays, providing flexibility in impression-taking techniques to suit individual patient needs and preferences.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-03 23:28:02\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:41:27\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:40:31\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-03 23:28:02\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlbtext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlc\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlctext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetc\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"attribs\":\"{\\\"article_layout\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_titles\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_tags\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_create_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_modify_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publish_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_item_navigation\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_hits\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_noauth\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urls_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"alternative_readmore\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"article_page_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publishing_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_article_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_backend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_article_format\\\":\\\"standard\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_audio\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_gallery\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_video\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"version\":11,\"ordering\":1,\"metakey\":\"\",\"metadesc\":\"\",\"access\":1,\"hits\":0,\"metadata\":\"{\\\"robots\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"rights\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"featured\":\"0\",\"language\":\"*\",\"note\":\"\"}', 0),
(94, 'com_content.article.9', '', '2024-05-24 02:42:56', 748, 5013, '44aab1f541ce5e42dd856ee519107328fdd6add7', '{\"id\":\"9\",\"asset_id\":118,\"title\":\"Wax Sheet\",\"alias\":\"wax-sheet\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Wax sheets are thin, pliable sheets typically made from a blend of natural and synthetic waxes. They are widely used in various industries, including dentistry, crafts, and food packaging. In dentistry, wax sheets are commonly employed for fabricating dental prostheses, such as crowns, bridges, and dentures, as well as for creating diagnostic wax-ups. The sheets can be easily softened and shaped using heat, allowing for precise molding and detailing. Once cooled and solidified, wax sheets provide a stable and accurate model for further dental procedures. Available in different thicknesses and colors, wax sheets offer versatility and customization options for dental professionals and artisans alike.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Wax sheets are fundamental tools in dentistry, serving a variety of purposes in both clinical and laboratory settings. Composed of pliable and moldable wax material, these sheets come in various thicknesses and formulations to meet the specific requirements of different dental procedures. One of the primary uses of wax sheets is in the fabrication of diagnostic wax-ups, where they serve as a sculpting medium for simulating the desired shape, size, and contours of dental restorations. Dental professionals utilize wax sheets to create mock-ups of crowns, bridges, veneers, and other prosthetic devices, providing patients with a visual representation of their proposed treatment outcome.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Moreover, wax sheets are indispensable in the construction of custom trays for impression-taking procedures. Dental laboratory technicians heat and adapt the wax sheets over stone models of the patient\'s dentition to fabricate trays that precisely fit the oral anatomy. These custom trays ensure accurate impression capture and enhance patient comfort during procedures. Additionally, wax sheets find utility in the creation of bite registration records, occlusal rims for denture fabrication, and wax patterns for casting metal frameworks in removable partial dentures.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">The versatility of wax sheets extends beyond clinical applications, as they are also utilized in various laboratory processes. Dental technicians use wax sheets to create intricate patterns for casting metal or ceramic restorations, such as crowns, inlays, and onlays. The moldability of wax allows for precise contouring and detailing, ensuring the final restoration meets the patient\'s functional and esthetic requirements. Furthermore, wax sheets serve as a medium for dental students and professionals to practice their waxing and sculpting skills, honing their manual dexterity and proficiency in dental prosthetics. Overall, wax sheets play a vital role in dental practice, facilitating the fabrication of accurate and aesthetically pleasing dental restorations while serving as a valuable educational tool in the training of future dental professionals.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 04:31:38\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:42:56\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:42:34\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 04:31:38\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlbtext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlc\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlctext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetc\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"attribs\":\"{\\\"article_layout\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_titles\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_tags\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_create_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_modify_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publish_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_item_navigation\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_hits\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_noauth\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urls_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"alternative_readmore\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"article_page_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publishing_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_article_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_backend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_article_format\\\":\\\"standard\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_audio\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_gallery\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_video\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"version\":6,\"ordering\":0,\"metakey\":\"\",\"metadesc\":\"\",\"access\":1,\"hits\":0,\"metadata\":\"{\\\"robots\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"rights\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"featured\":\"0\",\"language\":\"*\",\"note\":\"\"}', 0),
(95, 'com_content.article.8', '', '2024-05-24 02:44:20', 748, 4913, 'd2211d7d51aea3469fd162ffebad67c8ba3b5ce7', '{\"id\":\"8\",\"asset_id\":117,\"title\":\"Self-Curing Tooth Acrylic\",\"alias\":\"self-curing-tooth-acrylic\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Self-curing tooth acrylic is a dental material commonly used for fabricating temporary crowns, bridges, and other dental prostheses. It consists of a powder and liquid component that are mixed together to form a malleable paste. Once applied to the prepared tooth or mold, the acrylic undergoes a chemical reaction that causes it to harden and set without the need for external curing sources. This material is valued for its strength, durability, and esthetic properties, making it suitable for temporary restorations that can withstand the forces of chewing and speaking. Self-curing tooth acrylic is an essential tool in restorative dentistry, providing patients with functional and aesthetically pleasing temporary solutions while permanent restorations are being fabricated. <\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Self-curing dental materials play a crucial role in modern dentistry, offering convenience and efficiency in various clinical applications. These materials, such as self-curing resin-based composites and acrylics, undergo polymerization and hardening without the need for external heat or light activation. This inherent ability to self-cure makes them particularly useful in situations where access to light or heat sources may be limited or impractical, such as in deep cavities or areas with restricted visibility.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">In restorative dentistry, self-curing materials are commonly used for direct composite fillings, dental bonding procedures, and fabrication of temporary crowns and bridges. Dental professionals appreciate the predictable setting time of self-curing materials, which allows for precise manipulation and placement before the material hardens. Additionally, self-curing materials offer excellent adaptation to cavity walls and margins, ensuring a reliable seal and long-term restoration integrity. Patients benefit from the reduced chairside time associated with self-curing materials, resulting in shorter treatment durations and improved comfort during dental procedures.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Furthermore, self-curing materials find extensive use in prosthetic dentistry for the fabrication of dentures, temporary restorations, and orthodontic appliances. The ability of these materials to polymerize at room temperature eliminates the need for specialized equipment or additional processing steps, streamlining the fabrication process and reducing laboratory turnaround time. Dental laboratories rely on self-curing materials for their versatility and ease of use in creating precise and durable prosthetic devices. Whether in the dental clinic or laboratory, self-curing materials continue to be valued for their reliability, versatility, and efficiency in meeting the diverse needs of dental practitioners and their patients.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 04:25:56\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:44:20\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:43:54\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 04:25:56\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlbtext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlc\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlctext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetc\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"attribs\":\"{\\\"article_layout\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_titles\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_tags\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_create_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_modify_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publish_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_item_navigation\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_hits\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_noauth\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urls_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"alternative_readmore\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"article_page_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publishing_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_article_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_backend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_article_format\\\":\\\"standard\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_audio\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_gallery\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_video\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"version\":5,\"ordering\":7,\"metakey\":\"\",\"metadesc\":\"\",\"access\":1,\"hits\":3,\"metadata\":\"{\\\"robots\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"rights\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"featured\":\"0\",\"language\":\"*\",\"note\":\"\"}', 0),
(96, 'com_content.article.7', '', '2024-05-24 02:45:25', 748, 5188, '0bdc907b2eab8b35515c002a81dd85ac9886c7c4', '{\"id\":\"7\",\"asset_id\":116,\"title\":\"Dental Flowable\",\"alias\":\"tm065-light-curable-dental-flowable-resin\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Dental flowable, also known as flowable composite, is a versatile dental material used for various restorative and cosmetic procedures. It is characterized by its low viscosity and fluid consistency, allowing it to flow easily into small cavities, gaps, or irregularities in the tooth structure. Dental flowable is commonly utilized for pit and fissure sealants, small cavity fillings, and as a liner under larger composite restorations. Its excellent adaptability and handling properties make it ideal for achieving seamless and esthetic results. With its ability to bond securely to tooth structure and other composite materials, dental flowable provides durable and long-lasting restorations that blend seamlessly with natural teeth.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Dental flowable composite resin is a versatile and indispensable material in modern dentistry, offering a wide range of applications and benefits. This low-viscosity composite resin flows easily into intricate dental cavities, narrow spaces, and areas requiring precise adaptation, making it ideal for a variety of restorative and cosmetic procedures. Dental professionals appreciate the excellent flow characteristics of these materials, which allow for effortless placement and contouring, ensuring optimal adaptation to tooth structure and margins. Flowable composites are commonly used as cavity liners, pit and fissure sealants, and as an intermediate layer in composite restorations to enhance adaptation and minimize voids.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Moreover, dental flowable composites exhibit properties that promote long-term restoration success, such as excellent wear resistance, polishability, and color stability. These materials offer reliable mechanical properties and durability, ensuring the longevity of dental restorations in the challenging oral environment. Additionally, flowable composites often contain radiopaque fillers, enabling clinicians to detect and monitor the integrity of restorations on dental radiographs. This feature enhances diagnostic capabilities and aids in the early detection of potential complications, such as secondary caries or restoration fractures.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Furthermore, the aesthetic versatility of dental flowable composites makes them an attractive choice for cosmetic dental procedures, such as direct veneers, minor reshaping, and dental bonding. Their ability to mimic the natural translucency and shade variations of tooth enamel allows for seamless integration with surrounding dentition, achieving lifelike and esthetically pleasing results. Patients appreciate the minimally invasive nature of treatments involving flowable composites, as they often require less tooth preparation and conserve healthy tooth structure. Overall, dental flowable composites represent a valuable addition to the armamentarium of dental practitioners, offering superior handling characteristics, durability, and esthetics to meet the diverse needs of patients and ensure optimal outcomes in restorative and cosmetic dentistry.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 04:21:03\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:45:25\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:45:11\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 04:21:03\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlbtext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlc\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlctext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetc\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"attribs\":\"{\\\"article_layout\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_titles\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_tags\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_create_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_modify_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publish_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_item_navigation\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_hits\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_noauth\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urls_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"alternative_readmore\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"article_page_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publishing_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_article_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_backend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_article_format\\\":\\\"standard\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_audio\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_gallery\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_video\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"version\":8,\"ordering\":6,\"metakey\":\"\",\"metadesc\":\"\",\"access\":1,\"hits\":0,\"metadata\":\"{\\\"robots\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"rights\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"featured\":\"0\",\"language\":\"*\",\"note\":\"\"}', 0),
(97, 'com_content.article.6', '', '2024-05-24 02:47:19', 748, 5301, '5be425de82de31e8311bd97ecb6b3217bf22fb63', '{\"id\":\"6\",\"asset_id\":115,\"title\":\"Dental Etching Agent\",\"alias\":\"tm062-dental-etching-agent\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">A dental etching agent, also known as an etchant, is a chemical solution used in dentistry to prepare the tooth surface for bonding restorative materials such as composite resin. It typically contains phosphoric acid, which selectively removes the smear layer and creates a microporous surface on the enamel or dentin. This roughened surface enhances the mechanical retention of the adhesive, promoting strong and durable bonding between the tooth and the restorative material. Dental etching agents come in different concentrations and application forms, including liquid or gel, to suit various clinical needs and preferences. Proper application of the etchant is crucial for achieving successful adhesion and long-term clinical outcomes in dental restorations.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">Dental etching is a fundamental procedure in restorative dentistry, essential for achieving reliable adhesion between tooth structure and composite resin materials. The etching process involves the application of a mildly acidic solution, commonly phosphoric acid, to the enamel and dentin surfaces of the tooth. This acid creates microscopic pores and irregularities on the tooth surface, which enhance the mechanical interlocking of the adhesive with the tooth structure. As a result, dental etching significantly improves the bond strength and longevity of composite restorations.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">The etching solution is typically applied for a specific duration, usually around 15 to 30 seconds, depending on the manufacturer\'s instructions and the condition of the tooth. It is crucial for dental professionals to ensure complete coverage of the etchant on the tooth surface during application to achieve uniform and effective etching. After the desired etching time, the acid is thoroughly rinsed away with water to halt the etching process and remove any residual acid from the tooth surface. This step is crucial to prevent over-etching, which can weaken the tooth structure and compromise the integrity of the restoration.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">Following dental etching, a bonding agent is applied to the etched tooth surface to facilitate adhesion between the tooth and the composite resin material. The bonding agent infiltrates the micropores created by the etching process, forming a strong and durable bond with the tooth structure. Dental professionals must carefully follow the manufacturer\'s instructions for the application and curing of the bonding agent to ensure optimal bonding strength and longevity of the restoration. Once the bonding agent is applied, the composite resin material can be placed and sculpted to restore the natural form and function of the tooth.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">Overall, dental etching is a critical step in the adhesive bonding process, enabling clinicians to achieve predictable and long-lasting results in restorative dentistry. By creating a micro-mechanical bond between the tooth and the restorative material, dental etching enhances the retention and stability of dental restorations, ensuring optimal patient outcomes and satisfaction.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 04:17:15\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:47:19\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:46:42\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 04:17:15\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlbtext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlc\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlctext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targetc\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"attribs\":\"{\\\"article_layout\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_titles\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_tags\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"info_block_show_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_parent_category\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"link_author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_create_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_modify_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publish_date\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_item_navigation\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_hits\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_noauth\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urls_position\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"alternative_readmore\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"article_page_title\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_publishing_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_article_options\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_backend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_image_alt_txt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_article_format\\\":\\\"standard\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_audio\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_gallery\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"helix_ultimate_video\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"version\":7,\"ordering\":5,\"metakey\":\"\",\"metadesc\":\"\",\"access\":1,\"hits\":0,\"metadata\":\"{\\\"robots\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"author\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"rights\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"featured\":\"0\",\"language\":\"*\",\"note\":\"\"}', 0),
(98, 'com_content.article.6', '', '2024-05-24 02:47:50', 748, 4842, 'c47f9b18a94cc502e95c42abcedb1960b23e7156', '{\"id\":\"6\",\"asset_id\":115,\"title\":\"Dental Etching Agent\",\"alias\":\"tm062-dental-etching-agent\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">A dental etching agent, also known as an etchant, is a chemical solution used in dentistry to prepare the tooth surface for bonding restorative materials such as composite resin. It typically contains phosphoric acid, which selectively removes the smear layer and creates a microporous surface on the enamel or dentin. This roughened surface enhances the mechanical retention of the adhesive, promoting strong and durable bonding between the tooth and the restorative material. Dental etching agents come in different concentrations and application forms, including liquid or gel, to suit various clinical needs and preferences. Proper application of the etchant is crucial for achieving successful adhesion and long-term clinical outcomes in dental restorations.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">Dental etching is a fundamental procedure in restorative dentistry, essential for achieving reliable adhesion between tooth structure and composite resin materials. The etching process involves the application of a mildly acidic solution, commonly phosphoric acid, to the enamel and dentin surfaces of the tooth. This acid creates microscopic pores and irregularities on the tooth surface, which enhance the mechanical interlocking of the adhesive with the tooth structure. As a result, dental etching significantly improves the bond strength and longevity of composite restorations.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">The etching solution is typically applied for a specific duration, usually around 15 to 30 seconds, depending on the manufacturer\'s instructions and the condition of the tooth. It is crucial for dental professionals to ensure complete coverage of the etchant on the tooth surface during application to achieve uniform and effective etching. After the desired etching time, the acid is thoroughly rinsed away with water to halt the etching process and remove any residual acid from the tooth surface. This step is crucial to prevent over-etching, which can weaken the tooth structure and compromise the integrity of the restoration.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-size: 14px; font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif;\\\">Following dental etching, a bonding agent is applied to the etched tooth surface to facilitate adhesion between the tooth and the composite resin material. The bonding agent infiltrates the micropores created by the etching process, forming a strong and durable bond with the tooth structure. Dental professionals must carefully follow the manufacturer\'s instructions for the application and curing of the bonding agent to ensure optimal bonding strength and longevity of the restoration. Once the bonding agent is applied, the composite resin material can be placed and sculpted to restore the natural form and function of the tooth.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":9,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 04:17:15\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 02:47:50\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 02:47:39\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 04:17:15\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\\"urla\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlatext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"targeta\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"urlb\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\