(117, 'com_content.article.12', '', '2024-05-24 03:09:54', 748, 4945, 'ffd49e71c131ee4a41e189b7805000b61bf86fbc', '{\"id\":\"12\",\"asset_id\":121,\"title\":\"Dental Handpiece\",\"alias\":\"dental-handpiece\",\"introtext\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">The dental handpiece is a fundamental tool in dentistry, utilized for various procedures ranging from cavity preparation to polishing. It typically consists of a motor-driven handpiece and a detachable bur or abrasive attachment. Designed for precision and comfort, modern dental handpieces are ergonomically shaped to reduce hand fatigue during prolonged use. They offer variable speed and torque settings, allowing dentists to customize the cutting parameters according to the specific treatment needs and patient comfort. With their high-speed rotation and smooth operation, dental handpieces facilitate efficient and accurate dental treatments, enhancing both practitioner performance and patient experience.\\u00a0<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">It is a fundamental tool in dentistry, essential for performing a wide range of dental procedures with precision and efficiency. Also known as a dental drill or dental turbine, the handpiece is a handheld instrument that utilizes rotary motion to cut, shape, and polish tooth structure and dental materials. Dental handpieces typically consist of a handle, a turbine or motor, and a rotating bur or attachment. The handle houses the motor and provides a comfortable grip for the dental professional, while the turbine or motor generates the rotational power necessary for the operation of the handpiece.<\\/span><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">There are several types of dental handpieces available, including high-speed and low-speed handpieces, each designed for specific clinical applications. High-speed handpieces operate at speeds ranging from 300,000 to 400,000 revolutions per minute (RPM) and are primarily used for cavity preparation, crown and bridge preparations, and other procedures requiring rapid cutting and shaping of tooth structure. Low-speed handpieces, on the other hand, operate at slower speeds, typically between 5,000 and 40,000 RPM, and are used for tasks such as polishing, finishing, and endodontic procedures.<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><span style=\\\"font-family: helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px;\\\">Dental handpieces may be air-driven, electric, or a combination of both, depending on the type of motor used to power the instrument. Air-driven handpieces utilize compressed air to drive the turbine, while electric handpieces feature an electric motor housed within the handpiece itself. Electric handpieces offer advantages such as consistent torque and speed control, reduced noise and vibration, and compatibility with a wider range of attachments and accessories. Additionally, some advanced electric handpieces incorporate features such as LED lighting, ergonomic designs, and programmable settings for enhanced functionality and user comfort. Overall, dental handpieces are indispensable tools in modern dentistry, enabling dental professionals to deliver high-quality dental care while maximizing patient comfort and treatment efficiency.<\\/span><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":10,\"created\":\"2024-05-04 05:06:17\",\"created_by\":\"748\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2024-05-24 03:09:54\",\"modified_by\":748,\"checked_out\":748,\"checked_out_time\":\"2024-05-24 03:08:53\",\"publish_up\":\"2024-05-04 05:06:17\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_caption\\\":\\\"\\\"}\",\"urls\":\"{\\